ork while at least a third are over-educated for the jobs they hold. The ongoing race for personal advancement and the focus on worker preparation have squeezed out civic education and learning for its own sake. Paradoxically, the focus on schooling as a mechanism of equity has reinforced social inequality. The challenge now, the authors show, is to create environments for learning that incorporate both economic and civic goals, and to prevent the further descent of education into a preoccupation with narrow work skills and empty credentials.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 7aEDUCATION / Educational Policy & Reform / General.2bisacsh1 aLazerson, Marvin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013 (Canada)z978311075606708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044220540uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/9780674037984zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674037984423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674037984/original  a978-3-11-044220-5  Harvard University Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-075606-7  HUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013 (Canada)b2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK